06506nam a22007335i 9780773564251DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19941994xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735642517 a10.1515/97807735642512doi  a(DE-B1597)657396  a(OCoLC)1394872573  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aGC1023.15bS43 1994eb 7aLAW0660002bisacsh04a333.91/64/09711 aLamson, Cynthia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSea Has Many Voices :bOceans Policy for a Complex World /cCynthia Lamson. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tForeword -- tIntroduction: Oceans Policy for a Complex World -- tCompeting Interests -- tResource Crisis: The Struggle in the Atlantic Fishery -- tAquaculture: Canada's Cinderella Ocean-Resource Industry? -- tAtlantic Salmon: Recreational versus Commercial Interests -- tCompetitive Edges: The Politics of Ports and Shipping -- tThe Eight-Billion-Dollar Question: Nuclear Submarines and Maritime Defence Policy -- tTechtronics: Canada's Ocean-Science Industries -- tConflicting Values -- tWhen You Can't Build Fences: The West Isles Marine-Park Proposal -- tNo Rigs: Controversy on Georges Bank -- tBuilding Alliances to Protect South Moresby Island -- tManaging the Arctic Ocean in Nunavut: The Inuit Land-Claim Settlement -- tCalculating the Risks -- tMurky Waters: Pollution in Three Atlantic Harbours -- tThe St Lawrence Beluga Whale: Will It Survive? -- tToxic-Shellfish Crisis, 1087 and Beyond -- tChallenging the Status Quo -- tSentinels and Saviours: Canadian Environmental Groups and Ocean Politics -- tGetting MEQ On Political Agendas -- tThe Quest for Excellence. Funding Marine-Science Research and Development -- tProspects: Towards a Three-Ocean, One-Nation Policy -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEach chapter describes the dynamics or tensions within a specific marine sector or policy community. Collectively, the contributors raise critical questions about the process, structure, and function of Canadian oceans policy, covering topics such as the Atlantic fishery, conservation, ocean science and technology, shipping, aboriginal rights, defence, and pollution. The book conveys a cautiously optimistic message: although Canada does not yet have a comprehensive oceans policy, there is growing evidence that the problem, policy, and political streams are converging. Canada must be ready to respond to this policy opportunity with clear objectives and appropriate program elements that mediate between competing interests and conflicting values. Those who construct Canada's oceans policy must be capable of calculating risks and challenging the status quo to create a workable, sustainable framework for oceans governance in our increasingly complex world. The contributors to this collection are Robert Boardman, Darlene Boyle, Mark Butler, Scott F. Coffen, Raymond P. Côté, Graham Day, Lloyd M. Dickie, Gaye Drescher, Wade Elliot, Terry Fenge, Julia Gardner, Robert Gorham, Cynthia Lamson, Josée M. Parent, Randall Prime, Barbara Riley, Timothy A. Smith, John Somers, and Jeffrey L.C. Wright.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLAW / Maritime.2bisacsh1 aBoardman, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyle, Darlene E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoffen, S. Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCôté, Ra